# Codex feedback - enum fidelity

Reviewed spec: `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-17-enum-fidelity-design.md`
Reviewed plan: `docs/superpowers/plans/2026-06-17-enum-fidelity-plan.md`

## Findings

### Medium - Canonicalization rules for open-world multi enums are contradictory

The spec gives two different answers for how unknown members in `multi + open` enums should be canonicalized. Section 2 says open members are preserved verbatim in the canonical key, but it also says the canonical form is a sorted, deduplicated, lowercased member list; later it says known members are mapped to `value_enum` casing while unknowns are kept when open; the testing section then says unknown open members are kept verbatim but lowercased. The plan then implements the lowercased version only.

That leaves implementers without a single, testable rule for whether `FooBar` and `foobar` should dedupe, and whether unknown literals are part of the canonical grouping key exactly as captured or normalized first.

Fix: choose one canonicalization contract for unknown open members, then make Section 2, the Task 3 implementation note, and the tests say the same thing. If the intent is to preserve literal provenance, the canonical key should not lowercase unknown open members.

### Medium - The composed `multi: true, open: true` case is in scope but has no acceptance coverage

The design explicitly says the flags compose, but the plan only tests closed multi enums, single open enums, and the migrated closed multi reference. There is no explicit validation or canonicalization test for the combined `multi + open` mode, even though that is one of the design's named target states.

That means the hardest branch can drift silently: the implementation could accept unknown members, but the dedup key, prompt wording, and rebuild behavior for the combined case would still be unpinned by tests.

Fix: add at least one end-to-end test for `multi: true, open: true` that exercises validation and canonicalization with a known member plus an unknown literal, or explicitly defer the combined mode out of scope.

### Low - GPT is most valuable at the control and synthesis seams, not the bulk summarization loop

The current Codex preset routes `codex:gpt-5.5` to every role (`src/open_deep_research/data/model_routing.json:34-41`), but the graph does not use every role equally. The supervisor node is the highest-control path because it has to plan, choose tools, and decide when research is complete (`src/open_deep_research/deep_researcher.py:400-451`), and `final_report_generation` is the main synthesis point where all notes are turned into the delivered answer (`src/open_deep_research/deep_researcher.py:962-1014`). By contrast, `summarization` and `compression` are throughput-oriented and already have cheaper, clearly separable jobs.

My view is that GPT is best utilized on `supervisor` and `final_report`, with `extract_facts` as the only other plausible step override if you want one higher-fidelity extraction seam later. Keeping GPT on every role spends premium capability where the graph is mostly doing routine compression work.

Fix: narrow the Codex preset so GPT is reserved for the planning/synthesis nodes, and route the bulk summarization/compression path to a cheaper backend.

## Summary

Proceed after fixes. There are no Critical or High findings, but the canonicalization contract and the combined-mode test coverage need to be made explicit before implementation starts.
